<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Asylum Support Appeals Project (ASAP) (LAI 0068)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About the Asylum Support Appeals Project (ASAP)</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 35.41pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ASAP is a legal advice charity specialising in asylum support law. It was set up </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in 200</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with the aim of reducing the destitution of asylum seekers by protecting their legal rights</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to food and shelter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. ASAP runs a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">pro bono</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> representation scheme, called the Duty Scheme, at the First</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-tier</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Tribunal (Asylum Support) (the Tribunal). The Dut</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y Scheme operates daily and appellants are assisted by ASAP staff and around </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">0 volunteer solicitors and barristers. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ASAP also provides training on asylum support law to voluntary sector agencies and runs a telephone advice line. We seek to influence asylu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">m support policy through research</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lobbying</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and strategic litigation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.41pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is no legal aid for representation at appeals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; solicitors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, barristers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and advice workers do not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> generally </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">attend</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. We are the only representation scheme. In 20</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">12 our Duty Scheme </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">advisers assist</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed in 455 cases, just over half the number of appellants with oral hearings</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We went on to represent 380 people in their hearing.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> In 2009 the Citizens Advice Bureau </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">published research showing that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> having legal representation before </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">heari</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng at the Asylum Support Tribunal increases the chances of success from 39% to 61 – 71% </span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.41pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e do not have a legal aid contract.    Destitute asylum seekers and failed asylum seekers can be entitled to s95 and s4 support respectively under the Asylum and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Immigration Act 1999.  If their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> applications are refused or their support is discontinued, they have a right of appeal to the Tribunal.  We are reliant on front line refugee agencies such as the Refugee Council, Refugee Action and the Red Cross</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">refer cases to us, and we support those organisations with submitting appeals and training.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hilst</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">organization do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es not use legal aid, our area of law is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dependent on it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Currently legal aid (‘Legal Help’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for advice and assistance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) can be used by solicitors </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> asylum support cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, but we believe far more assistance in applying for asylum support and dealing with appeals is done by the voluntary sector.  However legal aid is crucial in the development of asylum support law as will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be demonstrated below.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  It is of direct relevance to our clients when the Tribunal makes an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lawful decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  There is no right of appeal (in contrast to other First-tier Tribunals) and therefore the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> only remedy is judicial review (further detail</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> below</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">).</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.41pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We will respond to ‘t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">roposed introduction of a residence test for civil legal aid claimants, so as to limit legal aid to those with a ‘strong connection’ with the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.41pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The numbers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in bold and in brackets</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">below refer </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o paragraphs in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ‘Tran</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sforming</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> legal aid: Next steps’, the government’s response to the responses to the consultation paper</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ‘Transforming Legal Aid: delivering a more credible and efficient system’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.41pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We strongly oppose creating a system whereby</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> have legal rights they simply cann</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ot enforce.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is the first time legal aid has been removed from a category of person</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, as opposed to removing types of work from scope.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Most of our clients will fail the residence test</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">many of them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are failed asylum seekers.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The point has now be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">en made countless times but still needs to be repeated; the residence test directly conflicts with the rule of law.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  It is also unworkable for reasons set out </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by the Immigration Law Practitioners’ Association, among others.  Determining lawful residence is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> not a simple matter.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.41pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The government is concerned that migrants </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">access</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the welfare state (in its broadest </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sense) when</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> they are not entitled to.  However, it is essential that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the issue of some migrants obtaining benefits unlawfully is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">confused with the right to access what limited entitlements do exist.  Legal aid is concerned with the latter. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> It cannot be categorized with other aspects of the welfare state.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The government continues to make this error (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">113 - 114</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">).  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Since the late 198</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">0s when entitlement to mainstream benefits first began to be removed from some migrants a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> complex body of law, involving immigration, asylum, housing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, welfare benefits and social services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> statutes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and case law (both domestic and EU/ECHR) has developed.  Mi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">stakes are inevitably made by decision-makers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in what is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> widely</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> recognized to be a complex area of law dealing with fundamental human rights</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">residence test</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> remove</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the right to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">check whether decisions are correct and, if necessary, to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">enforce </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">access </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lawful entitlement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.41pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The government’s position is that the existence of exceptional funding under s10 of LASPO for excluded areas of law and for those who fail the residence test means that the UK will not ‘breach ECHR, EU or any other international l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aw obligation’ (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">116</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">).  This is far too glib; it is well publicised that a tiny number of section 10 grants have been made so far</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.   Many firms cannot afford to do the pro bono work required before, possibly, obtaining legal aid.  Frequently the reason the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK does meet these obligations is due to litigation being brought.  Removing the means of enforcement will inevitably </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lead to more breaches.  We strongly recommend that more time is given to monitor the use of s10 before it is burdened with being the sole </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">solution for all those who fail the residence test.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.41pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The government does not accept that the residence test cannot be implemented via secondary legislation and under LASPO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">117</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are sceptical that such a fundamental change can lawfully be brought in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by this method.  The government’s position will no doubt be tested in the higher courts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, with all the consequent costs and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">period of uncertainty for the vulnerable groups affected.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We also draw attention to the fact that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the changes brought in by LASP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">O deliberately left asylum support law within scope, for claims that concern homelessness</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (as opposed to s95 applications for subsistence only)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Initially, all of asylum support law was to be taken out of scope.   This amendment was made as a result of lob</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">bying from specialist lawyers, as it was conceded that these cases have more in common with homelessness (which remains in scope under LASPO) than welfare benefits (which does not). </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> However the residence test will directly affect the very group the LASPO </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">concession intended to help; failed homeless </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">destitute asylum seekers.  T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he majority of those who receive a negative decision from the Home Office on an application for asylum support, and thus require advice, are failed asylum seekers. In 2012, 91% of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> appeals we dealt with concerned applications for support from failed asylum seekers. We believe this reflects the overall picture of appeals at the Tribunal</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Nearly all of the cases we refer for judicial review concerned support for failed asylum seekers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (see section below on our 2012 referrals).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The government states that legal aid will be available for making a fresh claim (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">118</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and we welcome this clarification</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> As the government will be well aware, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">many</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ‘fresh claims’ are deemed not to meet the threshold set out in Immigration Rule 353, and so</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> not accepted as fresh claims.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> It is not clear whether someone making a fresh claim (who will by definition be a failed asylum seeker and so fail the residenc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e test) will also therefore be eligible for legal aid for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">other areas of law</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  If not, then the government, in removing work from scope, is switching between categories of people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and categories of law.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This is confusing and unjust and we strongly recomme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nd that if the residence test is deemed passed for one area of law, an exception is not then created such that the person still fails it for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">other area</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of law.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Once a fresh claim is made, an asylum seeker again becomes eligible for support.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If that sup</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">port is unl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">awfully refused or discontinued, there is a right of appeal to the Tribunal.   In the same way that this category will be eligible to judicially review the Home Office’s decision that they have not made a fresh claim, they should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be able to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> challenge an unlawful asylum support decision.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Home Office does not publish statistics showing why people are on s4 support, but the majority are due to having made further submissions.  The Home Office’s witness statement (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 59) in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">MK/AH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(see thi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rd table below) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">stated that in July 2010, 74% of s4 recipients had outstanding fresh claims, representing 4,512 people.  This figure then dropped to 45% by April 2012, which is also in line with our own statistics that 54% of our allowed appeals in 2012 co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ncerned people in this category.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We welcome the government’s concession regarding the 12 month rule and those granted refugee status or some other kind of lawful leave (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">119</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">).   However if an asylum seeker with a very strong case is granted refugee status </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">within 12 months of applying, they will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> then</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> have a further wait until they will pass the residence test.  This makes no sense. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> For example they may have a meritorious homeless appeal regarding which they will not be entitled to legal aid.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The governmen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t’s response is glib with regard to the concern that there will be an increase in litigants in person (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">123</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) and whether this would increase costs in other parts of the system.  No post-LASPO research is referred to, as presumably it is too soon for such re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">search to be in existence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, although we note the existence of the new Litigants in Person Programme Board</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.   It is very likely that there will be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> both</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> an increase in litigants</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in person and of unlawful decisions by public bodies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which go</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> challenged.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">   The g</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">overnment states that i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has ‘improved signposting to alternative sources of advice for those excluded from civil legal aid’ (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">123</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">).  It is not clear what is being claimed here; improved signposting or sources of advice.  There is little point in ‘improved </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">signposting’ if there is no actual organisations who can competently do the work, to signpost to.   Without much more detail, the impression given is of a piece with the rest of the proposals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; the government is willing to prevent vulnerable groups from enf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">orcing their rights.  This impression is further reinforced by the reference again to section 10 exceptional funding as the panacea to all the cuts.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We welcome the concession</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> made regarding particular vulnerable groups (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">125</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">), but we maintain that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">residence test as a whole is unlawful.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Examples, research and litigation</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Whether or not an asylum seeker as a determinant of legal aid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> </span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The following case studies illustrate the difficulties people have in showing that they are asylum seekers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">demonstratin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that whether they are or not should not be the determinant of legal aid eligibility</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Case study:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Mr A was assisted by a legal aid solicitor in making his application for support as well as his asylum claim. The Home Office had refused his application for support on the basis that they did not believe he had ever claimed asylum in the UK. His case was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> complicated because he had initially come to the UK through a third country to which he had been removed in 2006. But he had returned to the UK at some point and claimed asylum. Although the Home Office disputed this, he was able to show he had been inter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">viewed by the Home Office and had yet to receive a decision on his claim. The Tribunal judge found that he was an asylum seeker and he was granted support. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Case study: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Mr H had submitted further submissions to the Home Office following the refusal of his asylum claim. The Home Office rejected these saying they did not amount to a fresh claim for asylum. His solicitors then issued a Judicial Review which was settled by Co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">nsent Order. The Order made it clear that the Home Office had agreed to reconsider his fresh claim as an asylum claim. However, when he applied for support his application was refused on the basis that he was not an asylum seeker as his further submissions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> were still pending. It emerged in his support appeal that the Home Office caseworker had interpreted the Consent Order to mean that they were merely going to reconsider the further submissions, not that they had agreed they amounted to a new asylum claim.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> He won his appeal for support. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Case study</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">: Mr B’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">application had been refused on the grounds that it was not belie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ved he had an outstanding case.  However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, he had recently obtained permission to have his case considered by the Court of Appeal following </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the Home Office’s refusal of his fresh claim. He had been released from immigration detention but shortly after was admitted to a psychiatric ward as he suffered from serious mental health problems. He was thought to be at risk of suicide and suffered from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Post Traumatic Stress Disorder. He was sleeping in parks at the time of his support appeal.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> He won his appeal and was given support. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Connection to the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> as a determinant of legal aid</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is not the case that o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ur clients have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ‘little or no connection to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the UK’. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> They have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> almost always</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> been in the UK for several years</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and thus cannot be categorized as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">having ‘no connection’ with it. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Research we carried out in 2010</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">revealed that o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ut of 54 cases all but one person had been in the UK more than a year by the time we assisted them. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 67% had </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">over</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 5 years and in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 10</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cases for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">over</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 10 years. In that time they had forged ties to this country. Most had close family here an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d 23 children were included as dependents in the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> applications.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A small percentage will have paid taxes, on the basis that they had student or work visa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in the past.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However they will still not be eligible, as they will not have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">current </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lawful reside</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.   Under EU law (the Reception Directive) the government is obliged to permit asylum seekers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> who have not had an initial decision on their cases to apply to work.  Whether or not this rule applied to further claims for asylum was the issue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for the Supr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eme Court</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ZO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">(Somalia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(see</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">third</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> table below).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">These case studies demonstrate how persons who have a clear connection to the UK would be denied legal aid.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Case study: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Ms B arrived in the UK 14 years ago and claimed asylum. In 2009 she submitted a fresh claim to the Home Office which was still outstanding when we met her. Given the delay in considering her fresh claim, she had been granted permission to work and had take</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">n up a job as a care worker, paying taxes in the UK. In June 2012 following a change in policy the Home Office restricted the work she could do to the shortage occupation list. She lost her job. As she was not qualified to carry out any of the jobs on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">occupation list she has not been able to work since then and is now in receipt of asylum support.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Case study:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Mr M has been in the UK for 12 years. He now has two young children who are settled in the UK, one of whom is British. Although he does not live with his children he has regular contact with them and takes an active role in their upbringing. When we met h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">im he was in the process of preparing a further application to the Home Office on the basis of this established family life.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Need for legal aid </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">generally </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">for our clients</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In our experience, enforcing a legal right against a public body (which has already made a negative decision) invariably necessitates the threat of legal action. Often the threat, set out in a factually and legally detailed pre-action protocol letter is su</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">fficient for the public body to concede, and thus start to act lawfully.  If we are unable to refer our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">clients on to solicitors, they will become or remain destitute.  It is unrealistic to expect them to bring a judicial review as litigants in person.  No</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r, we believe, is this what the Home Office or the High Court would want. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">By way of example, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">residence test</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will prevent advice, pre-litigation correspondence and litigation in the following:- </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.07pt; padding-left:6.93pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Failed asylum seekers who cannot leave the UK (usually </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">due to lack of documentation) and have had their support appeals dismissed </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.07pt; padding-left:6.93pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Failed asylum seekers who cannot leave the UK due to medical reasons</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Failed asylum seeking families wrongly refused support under the Children Act</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Failed asylum seekers in need of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">care and attention under the National Assistance Act 1948</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Newly recognised refugees accessing mainstream benefits and housing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, granted status within 12 months of their asylum claim</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The purpose of the tables of judgments we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">set out below is to show that, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">were the residence test in force, many of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> these cases would not have taken place. We seek to demonstrate that it is in the interests of the relevant public bodies, not just migrants, that the law is clarified through case law.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is also in the interests </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the state and potential claimants that the law in this area can continue to develop. As will be seen from our tables below, many judgments from the higher courts are helpful to the central or local government, in defining and limiting their duties.  Rem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oving the ability to challenge decision-making will inevitably lower its quality.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The point has been well developed else</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">where, and particularly by the I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mmigration Law Practitioners’ Association</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (ILPA)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, that determining lawful residence is not a straightfo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rward matter.  The immigration status query we regularly deal with is whether someone is a current asylum seeker, as it is determinative of their entitlement to the main type of asylum support.  This is relatively simple compared to other examples set out </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by ILPA and yet this issue has generated two important Court of Appeal and House of Lords precedents which are frequently relied on by the Home Office, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Erdogan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Anufrijeva</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (see third table below).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Cases we referred for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">litigation in 2012</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As stated, t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">her</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e is no right of appeal from the Tribunal, and therefore potentially unlawful decisions can only be challenged by way of judicial review.   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> referred 19 cases to solicitors for consideration for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">j</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">udicial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">review</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and the details are set out in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">table below.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The majority were cases in which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the individual</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> had lost their Tribunal appeal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> against a decision by the Home Office to either refuse or discontinue their support. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The remainder concern</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> challenges to th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e UKBA policy or practice, such </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">automatic dispersal from London, regardless of the fact of the case. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(and potentially 2 more) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the claimants would not be entitled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> legal aid under the residence test</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Out of the 19 cases referred to solicit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ors, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5 were considered too weak to pursue.  In the remaining 14, proceedings were issued in 12 and the Home Office backed down after pre-action protocol letter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in 2.  Regarding the 12, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> were settled on the basis of the claimants receiving support.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  In 3 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">permission and/or interim relief was refused, and 2 remain outstanding.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In 6 cases, the claimants </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">had been refused support on the grounds that they were not considered to be taking enough steps to leave the UK voluntarily and return to their countries of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">origins.   In all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">one of these,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the claimants were successful in overturning the UKBA decision and thus obtained</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> support.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Case study: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The particular difficulties these individuals will experience when trying to leave the UK is highlighted by the case </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">of Mr A, who is a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Bidoon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> from Kuwait.   In common with many Kuwaiti </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Bidoons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, Mr A and his family had lived Kuwait for many years but never acquired Kuwaiti citizenship.   Whilst in UK he had approached the Kuwaiti embassy several times to try and obtain do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">cuments to return but these were refused on the basis that he was not a national of Kuwait.  Following a decision by the Tribunal to refuse him support on the basis that he was not taking enough steps to return, we referred his case to a solicitor.   Durin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">g the process of the judicial review, the Treasury Solicitor settled and agreed to grant him support and to backdate this to the day of his appeal hearing.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Case Study: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">This is illustrated by the case of Mr B who, following a successful appeal, was offere</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">d accommodation in Wales.   However, his partner and two young children were housed in London which would have severely limited the contact he could have with them.   The solicitors issued a letter before claim, pointing out Home Office’s duties to promote</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> the welfare of children and also their obligations to preserve family life as far as possible.  Following the letter, UKBA agreed to house Mr B close to his family in London thus ensuring he had sufficient contact with his partner and children.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Table show</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ing ASAP referrals to solicitors </span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:480.3pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:47.95pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Date </span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; bord