">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:133.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">No – subject matter of proceedings</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:311.4pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:90.45pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Nigatu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) v SSHD</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">[2004] EWHC 1806</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:255.15pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Issue of what counts as fresh claim so as to trigger entitlement to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">support (so crucial to the proposals as the same ‘threshold’ is being used to decide entitlement to legal aid, 3.58). By time of full hearing of JR took place, the SSHD had accepted it as a fresh claim but Mr Justice Collins decided issue of importance so </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should proc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eed.  N </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">had attempted to apply for support, but NASS refused it although they acknowledged that the HO had received his fresh claim (applications for s4 support prior to 2005 did not lead to an appeal and so JR was the only remedy here).  Judgme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nt quotes Bingham in CA in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Onibiyo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 1996 on why the Refugee Convention must allow for fresh claims, and what test should be to qualify as one (new material etc) and that if it is a fresh claim, then there must be a right of appeal. And that JR is the correc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t remedy to use to compel the SSHD, if he errs, to accept it as a fresh claim. But therefore making a fresh claim and it being accepted as one are 2 separate stages, and only the latter triggers entitlement to s95 support</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:133.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Unclear</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Case contains essential </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">guidance to both sides on when a ‘fresh claim’ is made, and therefore when asylum support (s95 or s4) becomes available.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Although there will now be legal aid to make a fresh claim, it is unclear as to whether there will be legal aid for the same asylum se</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eker for an asylum support law case </span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:147.7pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:90.45pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Erdogan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) v SSHD</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">[2004] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 1087</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:255.15pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">On issue of when an asylum-seeker fails to appeal an asylum refusal in time, and instead submits an out of time appeal, and whether remains entitled to s95 support. The CA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">allowed the SSHD’s appeal.  Useful guidance on purpose of the asylum support system, and mechanisms to prevent it being abused (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 19), and also on the importance of the ‘supervisory role of the court in judicial review to give protection where necessary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’ (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 20)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:133.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Unclear, as above</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:174.55pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:90.45pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Limbuela</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tesema</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and Adam) v SSHD</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Shelter as intervener</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">[2006] UKHL 66</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:255.15pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">IAA 1999 s55 preventing asylum support from those who did not claim on arrival.  All 5 law lords dismissed the SSHD’s appeal, and confirmed that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">this was a breach or Art 3. The SSHD had also lost at the High Court stage</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:133.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Yes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">BUT</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the implication of 3.57 is that they will lose legal aid if they are refused asylum, even for an ongoing case.  Therefore this test case would never have reached the lords.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Limbuela</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> became a failed  asylum seeker, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tesema</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and Adam  became refugees so query whether legal aid would have continued for those two, as a test case)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:126.65pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:90.45pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R (AW,A,Y) v Croydon, Hackney</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">SSHD as interested  party      </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">[2007] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Civ</span><span style="font-fa