0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Mind and Freedom from Torture as interveners</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#ff0000; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">[2013] UKSC 27</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:255.15pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">On the meaning of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the NAA s21 ‘care and attention’ and when a vulnerable asylum-seeker becomes the responsibility of a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local authority </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as opposed to the UKBA (either under s95 or s4).  Existing authorities reviewed and the CA’s judgment overturned, and held that the care a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nd </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">attention needs to be ‘accommodation-related’. Very useful guidance given by the Supreme Court (SC) on this ‘unseemly turf war’ between </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and central govt (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 2)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:133.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">unclear</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">When the case started SL was a failed asylum-seeker and by time</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it reached the SC he had </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ILR</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">We do not have complete statistics from the Tribunal for 2012 so this figure is based on six months of 2012. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> CAB Evidence Briefing: Supporting Justice, The case for publicly funded legal representation before the Asylum Support Tribunal, Citizens Advice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Bureau, June 2009  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> We are unable to provide figures from the Tribunal as they do not publish this information. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> ASAP, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">No Credibility: UKBA Decision making and Section 4 support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> (April 2011) available on our website at </span><a href="http://www.asaproject.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/no-credibility.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.asaproject.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/no-credibility.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>